4. Prior Prototype Assessment

4.1 Prototype I: Primo

Designation: Maritime Social Integration Unit
Primary Material: Standard valley clay
Primary Strength: Immediate belonging through usefulness and near-smiling
Primary Vulnerability: Hydrological reabsorption
Outcome: Dissolution at sea
Learning Captured: Clay intended for fishermen must be rendered less philosophically available to water.

Primo demonstrated exceptional capacity for observational learning, professional humility, and tide-based competence. His eventual softening revealed a critical flaw in the first-generation porous-body architecture.

The Primo Event established the necessity of environmental compatibility assessment prior to vocational release.

4.2 Prototype II: Yiorgos

Designation: Agrarian Continuity and Livestock Preservation Unit
Primary Material: Dense upland clay with fired-clay particulate reinforcement
Primary Strength: Soil stewardship, patient labour, equine attachment
Primary Vulnerability: Thermal compromise under heroic stable-entry conditions
Outcome: Structural separation during fire-based rescue operation
Learning Captured: Waterproofing is not fireproofing, and moral strength is not a ceramic property.

Yiorgos achieved significant land-use stabilisation and olive-grove yield enhancement. His death in the rescue of Kephos demonstrated high-value ethical performance but exposed the inadequacy of surface sealing under extreme heat.

The Yiorgos Event generated the first formal need for integrated strength rather than mere density.

4.3 Prototype III: Atlas

Designation: Mountain-Pass Guardian and Load-Bearing Intervention Unit
Primary Material: Repeatedly fired, reground, high-resistance clay composite
Primary Strength: Crisis containment, compressive courage, spatial authority
Primary Vulnerability: Sacrificial overcompliance during geological emergency
Outcome: Burial beneath pass-collapse debris
Learning Captured: A person designed to hold may hold beyond survivability.

Atlas represented the most structurally ambitious clay-man output to date. His final act preserved Kamile and the tools necessary for future production, thereby transforming himself from prototype into enabling infrastructure.

The Atlas Event confirmed that succession is not only technical. It is moral, burdensome, and frequently located under several tons of stone.

4.4 Succession Candidate: Androcles

Designation: Human Apprentice, Post-War Creative Rehabilitation Track
Primary Material: Mortal flesh, regret, retrained hands
Primary Strength: Unlearning force, late-life seriousness, ethical motivation
Primary Vulnerability: Unscheduled divine lightning
Outcome: Total reduction without residue
Learning Captured: Apprenticeship continuity cannot rely on a single non-redundant human asset within range of celestial conflict.

Androcles was not a clay man, but his importance to the initiative cannot be overstated. He represented the first viable pathway by which the craft might outlive the original soul donor.

His loss created the Androcles Gap, defined as the sudden absence of the only person who understood both the shaping of clay and the necessity of continuing.

