12. Ethical Considerations

12.1 Consent

Loretto cannot consent to being created prior to creation. This remains a known limitation of all birth, clay-based or otherwise.

Post-creation consent shall be respected to the extent compatible with the fact that he will already exist.

12.2 Instrumentalisation

The initiative recognises the danger of making a person for a purpose. It also recognises that the gods made Kamile for precisely such a purpose and provided no complaint procedure.

To mitigate instrumentalisation, Loretto shall be given language, history, practical knowledge, and the right to decide whether victory is continuation, refusal, or departure.

12.3 Sacrificial Burden

Kamile’s final soul transfer constitutes both self-loss and fulfilment. The ethical status of this act remains unresolved and shall be filed under Voluntary Compulsion, a category created specifically to avoid resolving it.

12.4 Joy as Evidence

Kamile’s joy cannot be dismissed as divine manipulation simply because it was planted by the gods. Many things are planted and later become their own.

The initiative therefore recognises joy as admissible evidence, though not conclusive proof.

