15. Theological Positioning

The initiative neither rejects nor affirms divine ownership of the work. Instead, it adopts the position that an act may originate in divine intention and still become human through suffering, repetition, and choice.

This position is known as the Hephaestean Ambiguity Doctrine, although Hephaestus has neither confirmed nor denied jurisdiction over the hills.

Under this doctrine:

1. Gifts may be burdens.
2. Burdens may be loves.
3. Loves may be instruments.
4. Instruments may be used incorrectly by their users.
5. A mortal who completes a divine design knowingly may still be said to have acted freely.
6. This conclusion is provisional and should not be shown to priests.

